## Instructions

1. Read the SPEC at /workspaces/Contracts/dojo/SPEC.md and the schema at /workspaces/Contracts/dojo/schema/node.schema.json for the exact node.json format.
2. Look at /workspaces/Contracts/dojo/nodes/github/repos/node.json as a reference for a well-formed skill node. Also reference https://github.com/agentskills/agentskills for the Agent Skills format.
3. Research the official documentation for "mcp" — use WebFetch to pull docs, API references, CLI help, and examples.
4. For each node in the target tree above, create a node.json file in the appropriate directory under /workspaces/Contracts/dojo/nodes/.
5. Make every node rich: context, info, body with wiki-links, sections, aliases, triggers, links, related, tags.
6. For skill and sub nodes, include scripts with real commands/code, schema with input/output, env vars, and depends.
7. Create parent directories as needed (mkdir -p).
8. Do NOT ask questions. Do NOT ask for confirmation. Just build the nodes.
9. After creating all nodes, validate that each node.json is valid JSON and conforms to the schema.
10. If you also want to create a SKILL.md for any executable skill, place it next to the node.json in the same directory.

Quality bar:
- context: one line, under 200 chars, tells an agent when to use this node
- info: dense paragraph with scope, execution surface, and why it matters
- body: long-form markdown with [[uri]] wiki-links, code examples, environment variables
- sections: addressable chunks with ids, titles, bodies, and tags
- aliases: real phrases agents and users say
- triggers: natural language phrases that should surface this node
- links: directed next steps to related nodes
- related: semantic relationships (prerequisite, see-also, implements, extends)
- scripts: real executable commands, not placeholders
- schema: real input/output contracts

Do not produce placeholder or skeleton nodes. Every node must teach well enough that another agent can learn and act from it without reading upstream docs.
